UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1386418199000051
KW  - Financial exchanges
AB  - This article presents theory and evidence regarding the organization of financial exchange markets. It derives conditions under which (1) a member-owned exchange has a monopoly over the trade of a particular financial contract and its close substitutes, and (2) exchange members earn economic rents. Given these conditions, low cost suppliers of financial services form an exchange that is large enough to deter entry by competing exchanges but which is smaller than optimal. However, exchanges trading differentiated products may not merge to exploit all scope economies. Furthermore, exchanges that offer a variety of products may allow some members to trade only a subset of these products in order to preserve member rents. The evidence regarding exchange market shares, rents, and membership policies is broadly consistent with these predictions.
ER  - 
